<p>There's bad news and good news for the Parkinson's community: Parkinson's disease is on the rise, but so are better treatments.</p>
<p>For almost 50 years, we've relied on levodopa (namely Sinemet -- carbidopa/levodopa) as the gold standard of symptomatic therapy of Parkinson's disease. This medication is safe, well-tolerated and effective for motor symptoms but comes with the potential side effect of motor fluctuations. Relatively few updates to this drug have occurred over the years. In early 2015, however, two new formulations were approved and several others are currently in mid-to-late stages of clinical testing.</p>
<p><strong>Download this article, written by Rachel Dolhun, MD, to read the latest in levodopa therapy relevant to your patients and your practice.</strong></p>
<p><strong>Read about:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Benefits and side effects of current drugs</strong></li>
<li><strong>Latest therapies -- Rytary and Duopa</strong></li>
<li><strong>Drugs in development -- liquid levodopa and rescue medications</strong></li>
</ul>

